Temporal logic to express non-Markovian aspects has a history   containing, e.g., Linear Temporal Logic  (LTL). It uses the standard Boolean connectives of propositional logic, i.e. ∧\land, ∨\lor and ¬\lnot, with the addition of temporal connectives G𝐺G (always), F𝐹F (eventually), X𝑋X (next) and U𝑈U (until). More recent variations restrict to finite traces: Linear Temporal Logic over Finite Traces, denoted LTLf, and Linear Dynamic Logic over Finite Traces which allows for regular expressivity . Using LDLf, goals can be as expressive as regular expressions while at the same time providing a more attractive specification syntax. Formally, LDLf formulae ϕitalic-ϕ\phi can be built using an atomic property 𝑡𝑡𝑡𝑡\mathit{tt} for the logical 𝑡𝑟𝑢𝑒𝑡𝑟𝑢𝑒\mathit{true}, a propositional formula φ𝜑\varphi and a path expression ρ𝜌\rho, which is a regular expression over propositional formulae ϕitalic-ϕ\phi. In addition to regular expression constructs, ρ𝜌\rho uses a test construct φ​?𝜑?\varphi?, indicating to only continue evaluation when φ𝜑\varphi evaluates to 𝑡𝑟𝑢𝑒𝑡𝑟𝑢𝑒\mathit{true}. The LDLf formalism, as presented by , is expressed in Equations 2 and 3. Intuitively, one may interpret LDLf formula ⟨ϱ⟩​φdelimited-⟨⟩italic-ϱ𝜑\langle\varrho\rangle\varphi as stating that, from the current step in the trace, there exists at least one (cf. ∃\exists) execution path that satisfies regular expression ϱitalic-ϱ\varrho such that the last step in the trace satisfies φ𝜑\varphi. Conversely, [ϱ]​φdelimited-[]italic-ϱ𝜑[\varrho]\varphi states that, from the current step in the trace, all (cf. ∀for-all\forall) execution paths satisfying regular expression ϱitalic-ϱ\varrho are such that the last step in that execution path satisfies φ𝜑\varphi. For example, to formalize the property of a robotic waiter to always serve guests after they have placed an order, the formula [𝑡𝑟𝑢𝑒∗](𝑜𝑟𝑑𝑒𝑟→⟨𝑡𝑟𝑢𝑒∗;𝑠𝑒𝑟𝑣𝑒𝑑⟩)𝑒𝑛𝑑[\mathit{true}*](\mathit{order}\rightarrow\langle\mathit{true}^{*};\mathit{served}\rangle)\mathit{end} can be used. Temporal formulae specified using LDLf can be compiled into Deterministic Finite Automata (DFA) . Formally, a DFA for formula φ𝜑\varphi is denoted Aφ=⟨2P,Q,δ,F,q0⟩subscript𝐴𝜑superscript2𝑃𝑄𝛿𝐹subscript𝑞0A_{\varphi}=\langle 2^{P},Q,\delta,F,q_{0}\rangle, where 2Psuperscript2𝑃2^{P} is the input alphabet containing all truth assignments to propositions in P𝑃P, Q𝑄Q is the state space, δ𝛿\delta the transition function, F𝐹F the set of accepting states and q0subscript𝑞0q_{0} the initial state. Core properties that can be expressed in LDLf are safety and liveness . A safety property is used to indicate that something bad should never happen, or something good always holds, and can be expressed as [𝑡𝑟𝑢𝑒∗]​⟨c∗⟩​𝑒𝑛𝑑delimited-[]superscript𝑡𝑟𝑢𝑒delimited-⟨⟩superscript𝑐𝑒𝑛𝑑[\mathit{true}^{*}]\langle c^{*}\rangle\mathit{end}, where c𝑐c indicates the good condition and the asterisk (*) indicates c𝑐c holds at every step up until and including the last step of the trace. That is, until the end of the trace, c𝑐c holds. Conversely, a liveness property indicates that some condition should be met before the end of the trace and can be expressed as ⟨𝑡𝑟𝑢𝑒∗;c;𝑡𝑟𝑢𝑒∗⟩​𝑒𝑛𝑑superscript𝑡𝑟𝑢𝑒𝑐superscript𝑡𝑟𝑢𝑒𝑒𝑛𝑑\langle\mathit{true}^{*};c;\mathit{true}^{*}\rangle\mathit{end}, where c𝑐c is the condition to be met. In words, eventually before the end of the trace, c𝑐c holds. Figures 1a and 1b visualize this. every picture/.style=line width=0.75pt [x=0.75pt,y=0.75pt,yscale=-1,xscale=1] [draw opacity=0][fill=rgb, 255:red, 78; green, 78; blue, 78  ,fill opacity=1 ] (250,20) – (310,20) – (310,80) – (250,80) – cycle ;
